This PR changes `provider.get_spendable_resources` to accept a filter which let's you define the target asset, amount, owner and also specify excluded resource ids.
It also adds `provider.get_inputs_for_filter` which works similarly to `wallet.get_inputs_for_amount` but with the advantage of being able to specify excluded ids.

It also adds a convenience method to the provider to retrieve the latest block time.

```rust
let filter = ResourceFilter {
            from: wallet.address().clone(),
            amount: coin_amount_1,
            excluded_utxos: vec![coin_2_utxo_id],
            excluded_message_ids: vec![message_id],
            ..Default::default()
        };
let resources = provider.get_spendable_resources(filter).await.unwrap();
```

While implementing the above, I made a bug which wasn't caught by our tests.
Because of that, I also added a test for `wallet.transfer()` for transferring asset ids other than the base asset.

Closes #765, #807

This PR introduces `ScriptTransaction` and `CreateTransaction`  which act as a wrappers for the script and create tx type. They both implement `Transaction` which guarantees that the type can be transformed to a `fuel-tx::Transaction` and be consumed by the client.

The wrappers include getters and builder-like setters to provide a better devx when creating custom scripts or reading the underlying tx from a contract call.

Building a tx:
```rust
let mut tx = ScriptTransaction::new(&inputs, &outputs, params)
                .with_script(binary)
                .with_script_data(data);
                
// or to extend inputs/outputs
tx.inputs_mut().extend(other_inputs);
tx.outputs_mut().extend(other_outputs);
```

Reading tx fields from a contract/script call:
```rust
let mut tx = call_handler.build_tx().await?;
let data = tx.script_data();
let id = tx.id();
```


Some other side-effects of this change:

- removed `ExecutionScript` since this abstraction doesn't provide any functionality at this point.
- constants and params were moved from fuels-core to fuels-types to avoid circular dep
- moved tx validity check to `provider.send_transaction()`

This PR fixes a bug in the launch custom provider and_get_wallets function where the coin_configs and messages were being omitted from the fuel node config file. The fix involves adding the coin_configs and messages to the initial_state of the chain_config variable, as seen in the updated code:

```rust
    let mut chain_config = chain_config.unwrap_or_else(|| ChainConfig::local_testnet());

    chain_config.initial_state = Some(StateConfig {
        coins: Some(coin_configs),
        contracts: None,
        messages: Some(messages),
        height: None,
    });

    if let Some(transaction_parameters) = consensus_parameters_config {
        chain_config.transaction_parameters = transaction_parameters;
    }
```

